#
# INC-2026-001 - NexaCorp Engagement
# Suricata Detection Rules - Phase 2 (FINAL v4)
#
# Analyst:    Johan-Emmanuel Hatchi (blue11)
# Created:    2026-05-11
# File:       /etc/suricata/rules/learner/lab.rules
# Target:     vsftpd 2.3.4 backdoor exploitation chain + Caldera C2
#
# SID range:  9000001 - 9000099 (analyst-local, no conflict with vendor SIDs)
#
# Version history:
#   v1: initial draft with $EXTERNAL_NET/$HOME_NET variables (HTTP parser)
#   v2: added flow:to_server,not_established to rule 9000003 (fix SC_WARN)
#   v3: replaced $EXTERNAL_NET/$HOME_NET with 'any' (lab uses all-RFC1918
#       subnets, so HOME_NET matches both attacker AND target → rules never
#       matched). Lab-specific fix; production deploy must re-introduce
#       proper net variables narrowly scoped to the protected segment.
#   v4: rewrote Caldera rules (9000004, 9000005) from `alert http ...` to
#       `alert tcp ...` with raw content matches because Suricata HTTP parser
#       is port-bound (HTTP_PORTS = 80 by default) and Caldera C2 is on 8888.
#       Removed flow:established from Caldera rules because Suricata's flow
#       state machine doesn't always settle during PCAP replay.
#   v5: post-review patch (2026-05-15):
#       - R6 (sid 9000006): widened scope from phpmyadmin-only to
#         admin|login|phpmyadmin via pcre (rev:1 -> rev:2). The v4 rule
#         msg claimed "admin/phpmyadmin path enumeration" but only matched
#         phpmyadmin, missing /admin and /login probes observed in I6.
#       - R6 tradeoff comment: clarified that the rule is intentionally
#         port-bound to 80 (the v4 comment incorrectly claimed port-agnostic).
#       - Finding ID references in comments: F-002 -> I2, F-008 -> I6
#         (alignment with the final report numbering).
#       - Replaced em-dashes in msg fields with regular hyphens for
#         consistency with fast.log output and the report.
#
# After editing this file:
#   sudo kill -USR2 $(pgrep -f suricata)
#   sleep 5
#   sudo truncate -s 0 /var/log/suricata/fast.log
#   sudo tcpreplay --intf1=ens19 --topspeed /tmp/attack_mtu.pcap
#   sleep 5
#   sudo grep -oE '\[1:[0-9]+:' /var/log/suricata/fast.log | sort | uniq -c
#
# =============================================================================
# RULE 1 - vsftpd 2.3.4 backdoor trigger (CVE-2011-2523)
# =============================================================================
# Goal: detect the unique exploit signature - a USER command argument ending
# with ":)" (smiley). This is the *only* condition that triggers the backdoor.
#
# Why this works:
#   - The FTP protocol carries "USER <name>\r\n" in cleartext.
#   - vsftpd 2.3.4 backdoor activates ONLY if the username ends with ":)".
#   - No legitimate FTP client uses ":)" in a username - extremely low FP risk.
#
# Why each keyword:
#   - alert tcp any any -> any 21
#     → port-21-bound match, any source / any destination (lab uses RFC1918
#       on both sides; production must scope this to the FTP server's IP).
#   - flow:to_server,established
#     → match only client-to-server packets in an established TCP session
#       (eliminates handshake packets from inspection).
#   - content:"USER "; depth:5
#     → match the literal FTP USER command at offset 0 in payload. depth:5
#       restricts the search window to the first 5 bytes for efficiency.
#   - pcre:"/^USER\s+\S*:\)\r?\n/i"
#     → strict regex: "USER " followed by any non-whitespace ending with ":)".
#       The \r?\n captures the line terminator. Case-insensitive.
#
alert tcp any any -> any 21 ( \
    msg:"INC-2026-001 - vsftpd 2.3.4 backdoor trigger (CVE-2011-2523) - USER ending with smiley"; \
    flow:to_server,established; \
    content:"USER "; depth:5; \
    pcre:"/^USER\s+\S*:\)\r?\n/i"; \
    reference:cve,2011-2523; \
    reference:url,scarybeastsecurity.blogspot.com/2011/07/alert-vsftpd-download-backdoored.html; \
    classtype:attempted-admin; \
    metadata:author Johan-Emmanuel Hatchi, mitre_attack T1190; \
    sid:9000001; rev:1;)


# =============================================================================
# RULE 2 - vsftpd 2.3.4 vulnerable banner (CVE-2011-2523)
# =============================================================================
# Goal: detect that a host advertises vsftpd 2.3.4 in its FTP banner. This is
# a "vulnerability exposure" signal, not an exploitation signal - useful for
# inventory & hardening triage.
#
# Why this works:
#   - vsftpd emits "220 (vsFTPd 2.3.4)\r\n" as its first server banner.
#   - Any host on the monitored network emitting this banner is running the
#     backdoored build (or a forensic copy of it).
#
# Why each keyword:
#   - alert tcp any 21 -> any any
#     → server-to-client traffic from FTP server.
#   - flow:from_server,established
#     → only server replies in established sessions.
#   - content:"220 (vsFTPd 2.3.4)"; depth:30
#     → match the banner string in the first 30 bytes of payload.
#
alert tcp any 21 -> any any ( \
    msg:"INC-2026-001 - vsftpd 2.3.4 vulnerable banner advertised (CVE-2011-2523)"; \
    flow:from_server,established; \
    content:"220 (vsFTPd 2.3.4)"; depth:30; \
    reference:cve,2011-2523; \
    classtype:misc-attack; \
    metadata:author Johan-Emmanuel Hatchi, mitre_attack T1190; \
    sid:9000002; rev:1;)


# =============================================================================
# RULE 3 - Inbound connection to backdoor port 6200
# =============================================================================
# Goal: alert on any incoming TCP connection establishment on port 6200,
# which is the hardcoded port the vsftpd 2.3.4 backdoor opens.
#
# Why this works:
#   - Port 6200 is not a standard service port (IANA: unassigned).
#   - Any inbound connection to 6200 on a host that doesn't legitimately
#     run a service on 6200 is highly suspect.
#
# Caveat:
#   - If NexaCorp uses 6200 for any legitimate internal service, this rule
#     would FP. To verify with client (recommendation in client report).
#
# Why each keyword:
#   - alert tcp any any -> any 6200
#     → target on port 6200.
#   - flags:S,12
#     → SYN flag set, no ACK - i.e., connection initiation attempt.
#       Mask "12" includes CWR/ECE for ECN, ignores PSH/URG/FIN/RST.
#   - flow:to_server,not_established
#     → fixes SC_WARN_POOR_RULE warning; explicit direction for SYN-only.
#   - threshold:type limit,track by_src,count 1,seconds 60
#     → throttle to 1 alert per source IP per minute. Avoid log flood if
#       attacker port-scans 6200 repeatedly.
#
alert tcp any any -> any 6200 ( \
    msg:"INC-2026-001 - Inbound connection to suspicious port 6200 (vsftpd 2.3.4 backdoor bind shell)"; \
    flags:S,12; \
    flow:to_server,not_established; \
    threshold:type limit, track by_src, count 1, seconds 60; \
    reference:cve,2011-2523; \
    classtype:trojan-activity; \
    metadata:author Johan-Emmanuel Hatchi, mitre_attack T1059.004; \
    sid:9000003; rev:1;)


# =============================================================================
# RULE 4 - MITRE Caldera Sandcat agent beacon (TCP content match)
# =============================================================================
# Goal: detect Sandcat agent beacons. Originally written using the http
# parser (http.method, http.uri, http.user_agent), but Suricata's HTTP
# parser is bound to HTTP_PORTS (default: 80) and Caldera C2 typically
# uses port 8888. Rewritten in TCP+content mode to match the raw HTTP
# wire bytes regardless of port.
#
# Why this works:
#   - Caldera Sandcat agent emits a fixed HTTP wire format:
#       POST /beacon HTTP/1.1\r\n
#       User-Agent: Go-http-client/1.1\r\n
#   - Both substrings appear in the same TCP packet (small POST request).
#   - "Go-http-client/1.1" is the default Go HTTP client UA - coupled with
#     "POST /beacon" the false-positive rate is negligible.
#
# Why each keyword:
#   - alert tcp any any -> any any  → port-agnostic, matches any TCP flow.
#   - content:"POST /beacon"        → exact byte match for the request line.
#   - content:"Go-http-client/1.1"  → UA match. distance:0 ensures it appears
#                                     after the POST line in the same payload.
#
alert tcp any any -> any any ( \
    msg:"INC-2026-001 - MITRE Caldera Sandcat agent beacon detected (POST /beacon + Go-http-client UA)"; \
    content:"POST /beacon"; \
    content:"Go-http-client/1.1"; distance:0; \
    threshold:type limit, track by_src, count 1, seconds 60; \
    reference:url,caldera.mitre.org; \
    classtype:trojan-activity; \
    metadata:author Johan-Emmanuel Hatchi, mitre_attack T1071.001, mitre_attack T1102; \
    sid:9000004; rev:3;)


# =============================================================================
# RULE 5 - Caldera C2 server response (TCP content match)
# =============================================================================
# Goal: complement rule 4 - detect the C2 server's own fingerprint. Like
# rule 4, rewritten in TCP+content mode for port-agnostic operation.
#
# Why this works:
#   - Caldera C2 server (aiohttp) emits a fixed Server header:
#       Server: Python/3.10 aiohttp/3.13.4
#   - This byte sequence in a TCP server-to-client packet is distinctive.
#   - Throttled to 1 alert per source IP per 5 minutes to avoid log flood
#     on persistent C2 sessions (Caldera beacons every 30-60s).
#
alert tcp any any -> any any ( \
    msg:"INC-2026-001 - Caldera C2 server response detected (Python aiohttp Server header)"; \
    content:"Server: Python/3.10 aiohttp"; \
    threshold:type limit, track by_src, count 1, seconds 300; \
    reference:url,caldera.mitre.org; \
    classtype:trojan-activity; \
    metadata:author Johan-Emmanuel Hatchi, mitre_attack T1071.001; \
    sid:9000005; rev:3;)


# =============================================================================
# RULE 6 - (BONUS) HTTP admin-path enumeration
# =============================================================================
# Goal: detect the recon pattern observed in I6 - same source requests
# multiple "admin-like" paths in a short window from automated tooling UAs.
#
# Why this works:
#   - The PCAP shows the attacker GETs /admin, /login, /phpmyadmin from
#     curl/7.81.0 and Wget/1.21.2.
#   - The combination of admin-like paths AND CLI HTTP user agents is the
#     fingerprint of automated reconnaissance tools (dirb, gobuster, ffuf,
#     custom scripts).
#
# Tradeoff:
#   - This rule is intentionally port-bound to 80 (HTTP traffic is overwhelmingly
#     on this port for legitimate use). A port-agnostic variant would need to
#     detect HTTP wire format on non-standard ports and increase FP risk.
#   - Two separate rules would be cleaner (one per UA), but combined keeps
#     the ruleset compact for the report.
#
alert tcp any any -> any 80 ( \
    msg:"INC-2026-001 - HTTP admin path enumeration (admin/login/phpmyadmin) from automated tool"; \
    content:"GET /"; depth:5; \
    pcre:"/GET \/(admin|login|phpmyadmin)/i"; \
    pcre:"/User-Agent:\s+(curl|Wget)/i"; \
    threshold:type limit, track by_src, count 3, seconds 300; \
    classtype:web-application-attack; \
    metadata:author Johan-Emmanuel Hatchi, mitre_attack T1595.002, mitre_attack T1592.002; \
    sid:9000006; rev:2;)


# =============================================================================
# RULE 7 - FTP USER enumeration (low-and-slow brute force pattern)
# =============================================================================
# Goal: detect the I2 pattern - a single source IP performing 5+ FTP
# USER attempts within a 30-minute window. This catches the slow-paced
# enumeration that Wazuh's built-in rule 11452 (12 in 60s) misses.
#
# Why this works:
#   - I2 showed the attacker tried 12 distinct USER values over ~2h40
#     visible in the PCAP, with cadence 20-90 min between attempts.
#   - The PCAP-visible 12 events lay below Wazuh's threshold but well
#     above this 5-in-30min slow-burn rule.
#
# Why each keyword:
#   - alert tcp any any -> any 21
#     → outbound USER commands.
#   - flow:to_server,established
#     → only client-side FTP traffic in an established session.
#   - content:"USER "; depth:5
#     → match the literal FTP USER command at start of payload.
#   - threshold:type threshold,track by_src,count 5,seconds 1800
#     → fire alert when same source IP sends 5+ USER commands in 30min.
#       Compatible with low-and-slow attacker cadence (no need for rapid
#       brute-force fingerprint).
#
alert tcp any any -> any 21 ( \
    msg:"INC-2026-001 - Possible FTP username enumeration (5+ USER commands in 30min from single src)"; \
    flow:to_server,established; \
    content:"USER "; depth:5; \
    threshold:type threshold, track by_src, count 5, seconds 1800; \
    classtype:attempted-recon; \
    metadata:author Johan-Emmanuel Hatchi, mitre_attack T1589, mitre_attack T1078.003; \
    sid:9000007; rev:1;)


#
# End of INC-2026-001 detection ruleset.
#
